Analysis of Boston Restaurant Data

Sacheverel Eldrid

April 19, 2019

Introduction

When this project was announced, I knew I wanted to do something with food. (Maybe the 11:45am - 1:25pm timeslot subconsciously affected my decision, but here we are.) After thinking it over for a few days, I decided I wanted to see if there was any corrolation between average incomes in Boston neighborhoods and the food offered there. In other words, where people could afford to eat out more - was the average cost of said activity higher?

Data Collection

For restaurant data, I settled on the Yelp Fusion API. Its incredibly intuitive to use, and only requires registering your App to receive an API key. This is opposed to Google Places that requires a cloud instance and a cloud account with free credits to eventually pull data that costs extra if you want pricing data which has the potential to snowball quickly. Now, the downside of course is for a restaurant to appear in the Yelp data, someone needs to have reviewed it. This does limit the datas exposure to new establishments, but as is this is more of a study on overall behavior of restaurant pricing I believe thats an issue that could be pushed to a more in-depth analysis down the road.

The other downside to Yelp, is it limits each query to a maximum result list of 1000 entries. So, if I were to try and GET all restaurants in Boston, I would only receive a list of 1000. The way this list is selected isnt really told to us either, so we have to assume its some internal logic that we cant attribute for. To get around this, I changed my query from GETting all restaurants in Boston, to individual GET requests for every zipcode in the greater Metropolitan area of Boston. Now, there still may be more than 1000 places in each of these locations but once we filtered the resulting 22000 entries for duplicates, our final Boston restaurant listhad around 4,000 entries. a firm upgrade of our original 1000 by 4 fold.

Now, with this unique-boston-rest.csv list we need to add a couple more columns necessary for aggregate analysis. Instead of doing this in the Python pull script, I felt it would be easier in R - so here we are re-filtering by the list of Boston area codes (in case the list of any zip included entries from outside townships), and then aggregating data per zip for a median price.

fixed_data <- read_csv("unique-boston-rest.csv")
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   Name = col_character(),
##   Rating = col_double(),
##   Price = col_character(),
##   PriceCount = col_double(),
##   Category = col_character(),
##   Lat = col_double(),
##   Long = col_double(),
##   City = col_character(),
##   Address = col_character(),
##   Zip = col_double()
## )
temp_fixed_data <- data.frame("PriceCount" = fixed_data$PriceCount, "Zip" = fixed_data$Zip)
#filtering for only Boston zips we have income data for
temp_fixed_data <- temp_fixed_data[temp_fixed_data$Zip %in% c("2151","2152","2129","2128","2113","2114","2203","2110","2109","2108","2111","2116","2210","2199","2115","2215","2118","2127","2120","2119","2125","2122","2121","2130","2131","2126","2136","2467","2135","2134","2163"), ]

avg_column <- aggregate(. ~ temp_fixed_data$Zip, temp_fixed_data[-2], median)
median_ratings <- data.frame("Zip" = avg_column$`temp_fixed_data$Zip`, "PriceCount" = avg_column$PriceCount)
write.csv(median_ratings, "zips-and-medians.csv")

The data doesnt make for a very good graphic on its own, but thats okay. The main use for this segment is to create a new csv called zips-and-medians.csv that well pull into QGIS as a feature column for each zip and create a heatmap. More on that below.

For income data, I used city-data.com. While they dont have an exact trail to where all their data comes from, they do reference public datasets and census data as the primary sources for population and income data with the more precise fields coming from commercial sources. Theres no easy way to download the selection specific to boston area zipcodes I wanted, so this was a manual process of copying the data from their website and storing it in a csv to eventually upload into QGIS as another zipcode feature column.

The rest of our data is locations and name fields necessary for identifying the neighborhoods and zipcodes of Boston. The majority come from data.boston.gov, in the form of zips, Neighborhoods, and Colleges.

Youll also notice a distinct lack of correlation between incomes and the color-coded map. Perhaps one of the most pronounced examples is comparing the incomes in Back Bay, a decidedly more expensive per restaurant area to Roslindale in the 1 $ territory. So while income may play a roll in restaurant prices its clearly not the deciding factor. Lets try something else.


Here weve added red dots for all colleges and universities in the Boston area. While there are a few outliers, theres a decided clump in the Back Bay area where restaurant prices are significantly higher than most surrounding areas. Now, as a college student I wont say were the only thing contributing to higher food prices but we certainly do eat out a lot. Weve also seen trends on and around campus specifically toward higher cost restaurants. Removing the Taco bell from Curry for a higher average cost Mediterranean eatery, and ABP leaving Marino to be replaced by Tatte. Which, funnily enough, both ABP and Tatte are owned by Panera and offer similar food options so the only real reason for the switch must be related to price.

R Charts

Pricing Analysis

Apart from all the location-based data crunching, theres also an opportunity to dig through the specific food data aggregating on type as opposed to zipcode.

First, lets take that same unique restaurant list and create individual restaurant entries for each tag given to describe the establishment. For example, if Amelias Taqueria is tagged as both Mexican and Tex-Mex, our resulting dataset will include one entry of Amelias with Mexican as a tag, and another with Tex-Mex. This is the easiest way to count how many times each tag appears throughout Boston without creating incredibly complex array manipulation methods.

fixed_data <- read_csv("unique-boston-rest.csv")
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   Name = col_character(),
##   Rating = col_double(),
##   Price = col_character(),
##   PriceCount = col_double(),
##   Category = col_character(),
##   Lat = col_double(),
##   Long = col_double(),
##   City = col_character(),
##   Address = col_character(),
##   Zip = col_double()
## )
split_cats <- data.frame(row.names = fixed_data[1, ])
#trying some freaky stuff
for(i in 1:nrow(fixed_data)) {
    row <- fixed_data[i,]
    categories <- strsplit(row$Category, ",")[[1]]
    for(j in 1:length(categories)) {
      rowTemp <- data.frame(row$Name, row$Rating, row$Price, row$PriceCount, categories[j], row$Lat, row$Long, row$City, row$Address, row$Zip)
      names(rowTemp)<-c("Name", "Rating", "Price", "PriceCount", "Category", "Lat", "Long", "City", "Address", "Zip")
      split_cats <- rbind(split_cats, rowTemp)
    }
    # do stuff with row
}

Now lets investigate what Yelp reviewers are saying is the most pricy food in Boston. Well skin down the split categories data frame into just price and category before sorting, finding the mean, and filtering for all categories that have more than 5 reviews. (That way if a type of restaurant is only listed once at a value of 1, it doesnt completely upset the crowdsourcing angle of this data). Im not surprised to see Steakhouses first, and organic stores not far behind.

Youll also notice some commented-out code relating to specific zipcodes. With a few line-switches, this is the same block I did analyses for most expensive foods per Boston zipcodes, but more on that later.

#split_cats
#Special code for per zip analysis
#zipped_cats <- split_cats[split_cats$Zip == 02163, ]
#skinned_cats <- data.frame("PriceCount" = zipped_cats$PriceCount, "Category" = zipped_cats$Category)
skinned_cats <- data.frame("PriceCount" = split_cats$PriceCount, "Category" = split_cats$Category)
avg_column <- aggregate(. ~ skinned_cats$Category, skinned_cats[-2], mean)
freq_column <- data.frame(table(skinned_cats$Category))
freq_column <- freq_column[freq_column$Freq > 0, ]
freq_column <- data.frame("Category" = freq_column$Var1, "Count"=freq_column$Freq)
skinned_cats <- data.frame("Category" = avg_column$`skinned_cats$Category`, "AvgPrice" = avg_column$PriceCount, "Count" = freq_column$Count)
skinned_cats <- skinned_cats[skinned_cats$Count > 5,]
expensive_cats <- head(skinned_cats[order(skinned_cats$AvgPrice,decreasing=TRUE),], n = 20)

Thank You

Expensive Food Map

With that, I want to stay thanks for sticking around until the end of this document and as a reward Ill show you my favorite restaurant graphic: most expensive foods per zipcode overlayed onto the heatmap of Boston:



Theres a lot to unpack here, but first: some considerations. Not every zip has every type of food and some are quite scarce on places to eat period. These you might guess are the ones with listings like Convenience Store or Grocery. Secondly, These arent necessarily the most expensive types of food in the areas. Where allowed (i.e.enough volume of restaurants for this condition to make sense) I filtered each list so each category had to have at least two locations in the zip to make an average. I didnt want to focus this analysis on if 02115 had one really fancy burger joint and no other places like Tasty Burger skewing the ratings. So these are the most expensive types of food on average. Pizza and Seafood seemed to be the winners, funnily enough.

I really enjoyed doing this project. While I went in with more tentative expectations for what Id be able to accomplish, after I had pulled in the Yelp data Ive spent the last two weeks just brainstorming any possible analysis I could think of to include. Some didnt make the cut, but a lot were easy enough to boil down into these maps and R charts. That being said there are endless other permutations of this data I didnt get around to but would love to explore so maybe Ill even update this page in future! Overall, Bostonography was a fantastic course teaching me every tool to do my own analysis on city characteristics and while I didnt necessarily prove my intiial hypothesis that average income level is directly tied to restaurant prices - I did find other factors like college locations and heaps of interesting information.
